    <!-- Page 1: Introduction & Architecture -->
    <div class="page">
        <div class="header">
            <h3>1. Introduction & Core Tenets</h3>
            <span>AWS Cloud Hardening Playbook</span>
        </div>
        
        <p>This document serves as the definitive reference for the PlanMaestro AWS security baseline. It provides a codified, opinionated, and production-ready architecture built exclusively with Terraform. The posture described herein is strictly aligned to the CIS AWS Foundations Benchmark v1.5 and is designed for multi-account AWS Organizations.</p>
        
        <h4>Core Security Tenets</h4>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Security by Default:</strong> S3 buckets are private and encrypted, EBS volumes are encrypted, and VPCs are isolated without implicit internet gateways.</li>
            <li><strong>Blast Radius Containment:</strong> Workloads are separated into discrete accounts within AWS Organizations, heavily restricted by Service Control Policies (SCPs).</li>
            <li><strong>Least Privilege Identity:</strong> Long-term IAM access keys are prohibited. AWS IAM Identity Center (SSO) with MFA is enforced for all human operators.</li>
            <li><strong>Assume Breach:</strong> Detective controls—including GuardDuty, Security Hub, and CloudTrail—are operationalized and alerting from Day 1 in all regions.</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Multi-Account Architecture</h4>
        <p>We deploy a 7-account architecture separating organizational management, security tooling, log archives, shared services, and environment-specific workloads (Prod, Staging, Sandbox). This ensures that a compromise in a sandbox environment has zero lateral movement path to production data or central logging resources.</p>
        
        <div class="box">
            Root Account (Billing only, MFA locked)<br>
            ├── Security Account (GuardDuty Admin, Security Hub)<br>
            ├── Log Archive (Immutable CloudTrail bucket)<br>
            ├── Shared Services (CI/CD Runners, Image Builder)<br>
            ├── Prod (Customer Workloads)<br>
            ├── Staging (Prod Replica)<br>
            └── Sandbox (Ephemeral Developer Environments)
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Page 2: Foundation & IAM -->
    <div class="page">
        <div class="header">
            <h3>2. Foundation & Identity Management</h3>
            <span>Phase 1 & 2 Execution</span>
        </div>

        <h4>Service Control Policies (SCPs)</h4>
        <p>Before any workloads are deployed, the foundational AWS Organization is restricted using SCPs. These act as organizational-level guardrails that cannot be overridden by any user, including local account administrators.</p>
        
        <div class="table-container">
            <table>
                <thead>
                    <tr><th>Policy Name</th><th>Prevention Scope</th></tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <tr><td><code>deny-public-s3</code></td><td>Blocks public ACLs and bucket policies across all non-root accounts.</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><code>deny-root-usage</code></td><td>Prevents Root user API calls (except unavoidable billing tasks).</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><code>require-imdsv2</code></td><td>Prevents launch of EC2 instances lacking IMDSv2 protections.</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><code>deny-unencrypted-volumes</code></td><td>Blocks <code>ec2:CreateVolume</code> if encryption flag is missing.</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><code>restrict-regions</code></td><td>Restricts resource creation to approved geographical regions.</td></tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </div>

        <h4>Identity and Access Management (IAM) Baseline</h4>
        <p>The IAM baseline ensures zero standing privileges. Developers interact with AWS exclusively via Single Sign-On (SSO) roles, while CI/CD pipelines utilize strictly scoped OpenID Connect (OIDC) roles.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Password Policy:</strong> Minimum 14 characters, require uppercase, lowercase, numbers, symbols. Prevent last 24 passwords. Expire in 90 days.</li>
            <li><strong>Permission Boundaries:</strong> All developer-created roles must attach an approved permission boundary limiting their effective permissions to a safe subset of services.</li>
            <li><strong>CI/CD OIDC:</strong> GitHub Actions assume roles via federation, tied exclusively to specific repository branches (e.g., <code>repo:org/name:ref:refs/heads/main</code>). Long-term keys for automation are strictly banned.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Page 3: Network & Data -->
    <div class="page">
        <div class="header">
            <h3>3. Network Security & Data Encryption</h3>
            <span>Phase 3 Execution</span>
        </div>

        <h4>VPC Security Baseline</h4>
        <p>The network topography follows a strict internal-first model. The default VPCs provided by AWS in all regions are immediately deleted upon account creation.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Private Subnets:</strong> All compute instances live in private subnets, routing outbound traffic through highly monitored NAT Gateways.</li>
            <li><strong>Security Groups:</strong> "Default deny". Explicit allow rules are required. Ingress rules permitting <code>0.0.0.0/0</code> for administrative ports (SSH/RDP) are actively auto-remediated by AWS Config.</li>
            <li><strong>VPC Flow Logs:</strong> All ENI traffic (accepted and rejected) is logged and stored centrally in CloudWatch and the Log Archive S3 bucket for forensic analysis.</li>
            <li><strong>VPC Endpoints (PrivateLink):</strong> Interactions with AWS Services (S3, DynamoDB, ECR, SSM) happen via private endpoints, completely avoiding traversal over the public internet.</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Encryption Standards (KMS)</h4>
        <p>To assure Data at Rest (DaR) confidentiality, Customer Managed Keys (CMKs) via AWS KMS are utilized extensively. Automatic annual key rotation is enforced across the board.</p>
        
        <div class="table-container">
            <table>
                <thead>
                    <tr><th>AWS Service</th><th>Encryption Method</th><th>Key Management Strategy</th></tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <tr><td>S3 Buckets</td><td>SSE-KMS</td><td>Account-level default CMK; rotation 365 days</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>EBS Volumes</td><td>AES-256</td><td>Account-level "Encrypt by default" enabled</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>RDS Databases</td><td>SSE-KMS</td><td>Dedicated RDS CMK with automated rotation</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>Secrets Manager</td><td>KMS</td><td>90-day automated rotation using Lambda</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>CloudTrail Logs</td><td>SSE-KMS</td><td>Immutable vault key; multi-region usage</td></tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Page 4: Detective Controls -->
    <div class="page">
        <div class="header">
            <h3>4. Detective Controls & Incident Response</h3>
            <span>Phase 4 Execution & Runbooks</span>
        </div>

        <h4>Continuous Monitoring Stack</h4>
        <p>Prevention inevitably fails. Our detective controls ensure rapid identification and automated containment of security events.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Amazon GuardDuty:</strong> Intelligent threat detection enabled natively across all accounts. Alerts on malicious IP communications, unexpected API calls, and EC2 compromises.</li>
            <li><strong>AWS Security Hub:</strong> Central aggregator for GuardDuty, Inspector, and IAM Access Analyzer findings, continuously measuring posture against the CIS Benchmark.</li>
            <li><strong>AWS CloudTrail:</strong> Multi-region organizational trails with log file integrity validation. Stored in an MFA-delete protected S3 bucket in the Log Archive.</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>AWS Config Auto-Remediation</h4>
        <p>We leverage AWS Config Rules combined with Systems Manager (SSM) Automation Documents to automatically revert risky configuration changes instantly.</p>
        <div class="box">
            ✓ s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited → [Auto-Remediates by stripping ACLs]<br>
            ✓ vpc-sg-open-only-to-authorized-ports → [Auto-Remediates by revoking rules]<br>
            ✓ restricted-ssh → [Auto-Remediates by removing port 22 global ingress]<br>
            ✓ cloudtrail-enabled → [Critical Alert generated if disabled]
        </div>

        <h4>Incident Response: Compromised Credentials Runbook</h4>
        <p>If an IAM role session or identity token is suspected to be compromised, the following standardized response is executed:</p>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Contain:</strong> Detach all existing policies from the user/role. Attach a strict <code>DenyAll</code> policy.</li>
            <li><strong>Invalidate:</strong> Revoke all active STS sessions using the AWS CLI: <code>aws iam put-role-policy --role-name TARGET_ROLE --policy-name RevokeOldSessions --policy-document ...</code></li>
            <li><strong>Investigate:</strong> Execute predefined Athena queries against the CloudTrail Log Archive to track the attacker's API footprint (specifically <code>sts:AssumeRole</code> and <code>ec2:*</code>).</li>
            <li><strong>Recover:</strong> Rotate the underlying identity provider secrets, notify stakeholders, and remove the Deny policy once cleared.</li>
        </ol>
    </div>

